    <h1>Conformational sampling</h1>
    <h2> Instructions</h2>
    <h3>Step 1.Setup of the starting 3D structure</h3>
    <h4>Case 1. The structure is downloaded by a X-Ray database (CSD or PDB)</h4>
    <p>Load the structure in a <a href="#Software">software of editing/viewing</a>
      structures and carefully check if the structure is correct. </p>
    <p> In particular:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Bond order</li>
      <li>Atoms valency</li>
      <li>Formal atom charge (and molecule charge)</li>
      <li>Ionization</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Case 2. The structure is build through the SMILES code</h4>
    <p>The SMILES can could be obtained in two ways:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>can be downloaded from various sources, e.g. ChemSpider, or
        can be </li>
    </ul>
    <p><br>
    </p>
    <h3><a id="Software">Software of editing and/or viewing</a> </h3>
    <h5>MOE</h5>
    <p>Commercial software that allows viewing and editing of small and big
      molecules.</p>
    <h5>Avogadro 1</h5>
    <p>Software that allows viewing and editing of small molecules.</p>
    <h5>Chimera</h5>
    <p>Chimera allows viewing and editing.It can be used to clean the file, e.g.
      it is possible to delete the protein portion of the file.</p>
    <h4>Vega</h4>
    <p>Vega allows a complete editing, e.g. it is possible to change the bond
      order</p>
    <h4>Vida</h4>
    <p>Vida is useful when the editing is not mandatory and it a visual check is
      sufficient.</p>
